            "ain_pid": "UQ:9227267",
            "ain_detail": "<p>The tourism industry is a key sector that generates millions of jobs worldwide. Before COVID-19, it contributed trillions of dollars to global GDP. A dynamic and uncertain global environment presents many difficulties in achieving a sustainable growth for the tourism industry. These uncertainties range from typical operational uncertainties relating to markets, technological change, and competition, to unexpected turbulence posed by exogenous events, such as global economic crises and natural disasters. A rapid decline of visitor numbers can also persist long after an adverse event finishes (e.g., natural disaster or political crisis) due to its lasting influence on destination images.</p><p>One way to address these challenges is for organisations to develop dynamic capabilities, which are important organisational capabilities that provide mechanisms to strategically adapt, adjust, or reconfigure resources and routines. Although a growing literature has noted the importance of dynamic capabilities in responding to a turbulent environment and achieving long-term resilience, how dynamic capabilities can be built in tourism organisations to facilitate crisis and disaster management remains unclear. The process of attaining organisational resilience through developing a portfolio of dynamic capabilities also requires further investigation. Therefore, this study aims to understand how tourism organisations can develop and utilise dynamic capabilities to achieve organisational resilience in crises and disasters. Building on the Resource-based View of Firms and the Evolutionary Theory of Firms, this thesis views dynamic capabilities as the mechanism that enables organisations&rsquo; response to the need for destructive environmental change through organisational process transformation, resource allocation and utilisation. This thesis includes four separate but inter-related papers exploring the role of dynamic capabilities in building resilience for tourism crisis and disaster management.</p><p>This study adopts a longitudinal research design and qualitative case study approach to investigate tourism organisations&rsquo; development of dynamic capabilities in a natural disaster context (i.e., Tropical Cyclone Debbie which interrupted the Whitsunday region in March 2017). In-depth interviews were conducted to understand: (1) the daily operation of their business; (2) impact of TC Debbie on their business; (3) changes in business priorities and activities in dealing with TC Debbie and its challenges; (4) factors that facilitate or impede their development of new activities and changes; and (5) processes of resilience building in a crisis/disaster time. The primary source of data for this research were semi-structured interviews, with document data serving as important triangulation and supplementary sources to gain additional perspectives. On-site observations were also conducted to gather information (using photos) about the changes and on-going construction by the tourism industry.</p><p>This thesis is presented as a series of four papers. The first paper is a conceptual study that builds a theoretical framework to show the process of resilience building in crisis/disaster times through the creation and selection of new operational routines driven by dynamic capabilities and slack resources. The second paper explores the enablers and barriers to building dynamic capabilities in tourism organisations to manage crises and disasters. Four types of resources (knowledge, financial, human-related, and relational) are identified as key enablers to develop dynamic capabilities; while key barriers exist in both internal and external processes due to the absence of shared value creation, which hindered the development of dynamic capabilities. This paper also compares how key enablers and barriers may differ across tourism organisations from different sectors, ages, and sizes. The third paper proposes a typology in the form of a matrix based on three key dimensions: disaster lifecycle (three management stages), source of resources (internal and external), and deployment of resources (exploitation and exploration). It summarises 12 types of dynamic capabilities, going beyond a simple classification of organisational activities in managing crises/disasters and acknowledged the critical role of organisational resources in coping with environmental uncertainty following the resource-based view. The fourth paper takes a processual view of resilience to investigate how tourism organisations use different types of dynamic capabilities to achieve resilience at multiple disaster management stages. A dynamic resilience framework was developed based on a series of resilience goals: situation awareness building, vulnerability reduction, adaptive capacity improvement, and disruptive change facilitation. Critical paths were identified in the framework to explain various possibilities to achieve a similar desirable outcome.</p><p>The thesis concludes with a chapter that integrates the four papers and discusses the contributions to extant knowledge and practical implications for the tourism industry and its stakeholders. By adopting the concept of dynamic capabilities from the strategy discipline, this research first advances tourism crisis and disaster research by creating a dynamic capability-based framework to highlight the transiting process towards resilience. It also can improve tourism organisations&rsquo; response to crises/disaster by: (1) identifying key antecedents of dynamic capabilities in turbulent environments and (2) developing a resource-based and disaster-specific typology of dynamic capabilities. Furthermore, this research reveals the processual mechanism of adopting different dynamic capabilities to achieve disaster resilience. Four types of transformation that could form disruptive changes are: (1) expansion of businesses from small to large scale, (2) restoration of businesses from destroyed to reconstructed, (3) revitalisation of the community from dated infrastructure to modern design, and (4) innovation of the industry from nonexistent products/services to newly established opportunities. A trial-and-error process was discovered that contributes to new knowledge for the reflection and resolution phases in tourism disaster management. These reflections of decision making and organisational performance could help to identify the most effective strategies in managing crises/disasters and possible reasons for success or failure.</p>"
